                <div id="s-lg-guide-main" class="tab-pane active">
                     <h1 class="page-title">
                     Beginning Your Research
                     </h1>
                     <div class="row s-lg-row"><div id="s-lg-col-1" class="col-md-12"><div class="s-lg-col-boxes"><div id="s-lg-box-wrapper-31587727" class="s-lg-box-wrapper-31587727">


    <div id="s-lg-box-26877854-container" class="s-lib-box-container">
        <div id="s-lg-box-26877854" class="s-lib-box s-lib-box-std s-lib-floating-box">
                        <div id="s-lg-box-collapse-26877854" >
                <div class="s-lib-box-content s-lib-floating-box-content">
                    <div id="s-lg-content-62242741" class="  clearfix">
    <p>Researching the history of the Star-Spangled Banner touches many disciplines including poetry, music, sociology, politics, and many more. Below are selected resources with which you can begin. You can find a wider variety of resources using the <a href="http://catalog.loc.gov" target="_blank">Library of Congress Online Catalog</a> using the subject heading &quot;<a href="https://catalog.loc.gov/vwebv/search?searchCode=SUBJ%2B&amp;searchArg=star-spangled+banner+song&amp;searchType=1&amp;recCount=25" target="_blank">Star-spangled banner (song)</a>.&quot;</p>


    </div>
                </div>
                
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</div><div id="s-lg-box-wrapper-30618651" class="s-lg-box-wrapper-30618651">


    <div id="s-lg-box-26053546-container" class="s-lib-box-container">
        <div id="s-lg-box-26053546" class="s-lib-box s-lib-box-std">
                            <h2 class="s-lib-box-title">
                    Summary
                                    </h2>
                        <div id="s-lg-box-collapse-26053546" >
                <div class="s-lib-box-content">
                    <div id="s-lg-content-62379346" class="  clearfix">
    <p>Below are three&nbsp;resources that will provide an overview of the history of the Star-Spangled Banner. The first, &quot;The Music of the Star-Spangled Banner from Ludgate Hill to Capitol Hill&quot; is a detailed history, the second, &quot;The Star-Spangled Banner (article)&quot; is more&nbsp;concise. The third, &quot;Printing the Star-Spangled Banner&quot; deals specifically with the song&#39;s early printing history.</p>


    </div>

    <div class="">
        <ul id="s-lg-link-list-62527196"
            class="s-lg-link-list s-lg-link-list-2">

<li class="">
    


<div id="s-lg-content-60140541" class="">
    <span>
                    <a href="https://www.loc.gov/item/77017183/" target="_blank" onclick="return springSpace.springTrack.trackLink({link: this,_st_type_id: &#039;2&#039;,_st_content_id: &#039;60140541&#039;,_st_inc_return: this});" >
                The music of the Star-spangled banner from Ludgate Hill to Capitol Hill <i class="fa fa-fw fa-external-link " 
    aria-hidden="true"
           title="This link opens in a new window"
   ></i><span class="sr-only">This link opens in a new window</span>             </a>
        
            </span>

    
    
                <div id="s-lg-link-desc-60140541" class="s-lg-link-desc">
            This study by William Lichtenwanger was reprinted from the July 1977 Quarterly Journal of the Library of Congress. It contains a comprehensive history of the song's creation and references to numerous primary source documents.
        </div>
    
    </div>

</li>




<li class="">
    


<div id="s-lg-content-60140830" class="">
    <span>
                    <a href="https://www.loc.gov/item/ihas.200000017/" target="_blank" onclick="return springSpace.springTrack.trackLink({link: this,_st_type_id: &#039;2&#039;,_st_content_id: &#039;60140830&#039;,_st_inc_return: this});" >
                The Star-Spangled Banner (article) <i class="fa fa-fw fa-external-link " 
    aria-hidden="true"
           title="This link opens in a new window"
   ></i><span class="sr-only">This link opens in a new window</span>             </a>
        
            </span>

    
    
                <div id="s-lg-link-desc-60140830" class="s-lg-link-desc">
            This article contains a short history of the song with numerous links to digitized editions at the bottom of the page under "related items."
        </div>
    
    </div>

</li>




<li class="">
    


<div id="s-lg-content-62383156" class="">
    <span>
                    <a href="https://blogs.loc.gov/music/2014/09/printing-the-star-spangled-banner/" target="_blank" onclick="return springSpace.springTrack.trackLink({link: this,_st_type_id: &#039;2&#039;,_st_content_id: &#039;62383156&#039;,_st_inc_return: this});" >
                Printing “The Star-Spangled Banner” (blog post) <i class="fa fa-fw fa-external-link " 
    aria-hidden="true"
           title="This link opens in a new window"
   ></i><span class="sr-only">This link opens in a new window</span>             </a>
        
            </span>

    
    
                <div id="s-lg-link-desc-62383156" class="s-lg-link-desc">
            A short article by Library of Congress archivist Ray White for the Library's "In the Muse" music blog detailing the early printing history of the Star-Spangled Banner.
        </div>
    
    </div>

</li>

        </ul>

        
    </div>

                </div>
                
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</div><div id="s-lg-box-wrapper-30618704" class="s-lg-box-wrapper-30618704">


    <div id="s-lg-box-26053595-container" class="s-lib-box-container">
        <div id="s-lg-box-26053595" class="s-lib-box s-lib-box-std">
                            <h2 class="s-lib-box-title">
                    Primary Sources
                                    </h2>
                        <div id="s-lg-box-collapse-26053595" >
                <div class="s-lib-box-content">
                    <div id="s-lg-content-62720692" class="  clearfix">
    <p>The following digitized primary source materials come from the Library of Congress collections, the University of Maryland, and Congress.gov.</p>

    </div>

    <div class="">
        <ul id="s-lg-link-list-64613103"
            class="s-lg-link-list s-lg-link-list-2">

<li class="">
    


<div id="s-lg-content-62243181" class="">
    <span>
                    <a href="https://www.loc.gov/item/ihas.100010457/" target="_blank" onclick="return springSpace.springTrack.trackLink({link: this,_st_type_id: &#039;2&#039;,_st_content_id: &#039;62243181&#039;,_st_inc_return: this});" >
                Defence of Fort M'Henry <i class="fa fa-fw fa-external-link " 
    aria-hidden="true"
           title="This link opens in a new window"
   ></i><span class="sr-only">This link opens in a new window</span>             </a>
        
            </span>

    
    
                <div id="s-lg-link-desc-62243181" class="s-lg-link-desc">
            This is the first printing of Key's poem published as a broadside in Baltimore on September 17, 1814 days after Key completed the poem.
        </div>
    
    </div>

</li>




<li class="">
    


<div id="s-lg-content-61096059" class="">
    <span>
                    <a href="https://www.loc.gov/resource/ihas.100010479.0" target="_blank" onclick="return springSpace.springTrack.trackLink({link: this,_st_type_id: &#039;2&#039;,_st_content_id: &#039;61096059&#039;,_st_inc_return: this});" >
                Facsimile of first newspaper printing of The Star-Spangled Banner <i class="fa fa-fw fa-external-link " 
    aria-hidden="true"
           title="This link opens in a new window"
   ></i><span class="sr-only">This link opens in a new window</span>             </a>
        
            </span>

    
    
                <div id="s-lg-link-desc-61096059" class="s-lg-link-desc">
            Published in the "Baltimore Patriot and Evening Advertiser," Sept. 20, 1814.
        </div>
    
    </div>

</li>




<li class="">
    


<div id="s-lg-content-60140946" class="">
    <span>
                    <a href="https://www.loc.gov/item/2014563896/" target="_blank" onclick="return springSpace.springTrack.trackLink({link: this,_st_type_id: &#039;2&#039;,_st_content_id: &#039;60140946&#039;,_st_inc_return: this});" >
                First edition of the Star-Spangled Banner <i class="fa fa-fw fa-external-link " 
    aria-hidden="true"
           title="This link opens in a new window"
   ></i><span class="sr-only">This link opens in a new window</span>             </a>
        
            </span>

    
    
                <div id="s-lg-link-desc-60140946" class="s-lg-link-desc">
            Printed and Sold at Carr's music store, 36 Baltimore Street, Baltimore: Printed and Sold at Carr's music store, 36 Baltimore Street, 1814.<br />
A second copy of the first edition is in the Music Division, pasted into a binder's volume compiled by one Mary Thomas. Call number: M1.A15, vol. 290, part 2.
        </div>
    
    </div>

</li>




<li class="">
    


<div id="s-lg-content-61096118" class="">
    <span>
                    <a href="https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn84024736/1814-09-28/ed-1/seq-4/#date1=1814&amp;sort=relevance&amp;rows=20&amp;words=banner+Banner+spangled+star+star-spangled&amp;searchType=basic&amp;sequence=0&amp;index=0&amp;state=&amp;date2=1820&amp;proxtext=star+spangled+banner&amp;y=10&amp;x=10&amp;dateFilterType=yearRange&amp;page=1" target="_blank" onclick="return springSpace.springTrack.trackLink({link: this,_st_type_id: &#039;2&#039;,_st_content_id: &#039;61096118&#039;,_st_inc_return: this});" >
                Reprint of The Star-Spangled Banner in a Richmond, VA newspaper <i class="fa fa-fw fa-external-link " 
    aria-hidden="true"
           title="This link opens in a new window"
   ></i><span class="sr-only">This link opens in a new window</span>             </a>
        
            </span>

    
    
                <div id="s-lg-link-desc-61096118" class="s-lg-link-desc">
            Published in the "The Enquirer," Richmond, VA, Sept. 28, 1814.
        </div>
    
    </div>

</li>




<li class="">
    


<div id="s-lg-content-60140712" class="">
    <span>
                    <a href="https://www.loc.gov/item/ihas.100000019/" target="_blank" onclick="return springSpace.springTrack.trackLink({link: this,_st_type_id: &#039;2&#039;,_st_content_id: &#039;60140712&#039;,_st_inc_return: this});" >
                The Star-Spangled Banner (manuscript copy) by Francis Scott Key <i class="fa fa-fw fa-external-link " 
    aria-hidden="true"
           title="This link opens in a new window"
   ></i><span class="sr-only">This link opens in a new window</span>             </a>
        
            </span>

    
    
                <div id="s-lg-link-desc-60140712" class="s-lg-link-desc">
            Item contains an autographed manuscript of "The star-spangled banner" in a red leather case. Also included is a portrait of Francis Scott Key, a copy of "The Star-Spangled Banner (Second session)", an advertisement for the song, a hand-written manuscript, and an article. Key's original manuscript is in the possession of the Maryland Historical Society.
        </div>
    
    </div>

</li>




<li class="">
    


<div id="s-lg-content-62353022" class="">
    <span>
                    <a href="https://collections.digitalmaryland.org/digital/collection/mhwe/id/21/" target="_blank" onclick="return springSpace.springTrack.trackLink({link: this,_st_type_id: &#039;2&#039;,_st_content_id: &#039;62353022&#039;,_st_inc_return: this});" >
                Francis Scott Key's original handwritten manuscript of "The Star-Spangled Banner" <i aria-hidden="true" class="fa fa-external-link-alt"></i><span class="screen-readers-only">External</span> <i class="fa fa-fw fa-external-link " 
    aria-hidden="true"
           title="This link opens in a new window"
   ></i><span class="sr-only">This link opens in a new window</span>             </a>
        
            </span>

    
    
                <div id="s-lg-link-desc-62353022" class="s-lg-link-desc">
            This is Francis Scott Key's original manuscript of his poem first published as "Defence of Fort McHenry" and later as "The Star-Spangled Banner." It is in the possession of the Maryland Historical Society.
        </div>
    
    </div>

</li>




<li class="">
    


<div id="s-lg-content-62353127" class="">
    <span>
                    <a href="https://www.visitthecapitol.gov/exhibitions/artifact/hr-14-act-make-star-spangled-banner-national-anthem-united-states-america-0" target="_blank" onclick="return springSpace.springTrack.trackLink({link: this,_st_type_id: &#039;2&#039;,_st_content_id: &#039;62353127&#039;,_st_inc_return: this});" >
                H.R. 14, An Act To make The Star-Spangled Banner the national anthem of the United States of America, April 21, 1930 <i aria-hidden="true" class="fa fa-external-link-alt"></i><span class="screen-readers-only">External</span> <i class="fa fa-fw fa-external-link " 
    aria-hidden="true"
           title="This link opens in a new window"
   ></i><span class="sr-only">This link opens in a new window</span>             </a>
        
            </span>

    
    
                <div id="s-lg-link-desc-62353127" class="s-lg-link-desc">
            A link to: H.R. 14, An Act To make The Star-Spangled Banner the national anthem of the United States of America, April 21, 1930. <br />
In April 1930 the House of Representatives passed a bill introduced by Representative John Linthicum of Maryland to make “The Star-Spangled Banner” the nation’s anthem. Despite critics who disliked the melody or felt the law unnecessary, the Senate passed the bill the following year, and President Herbert Hoover signed it into law on March 2, 1931.
        </div>
    
    </div>

</li>

        </ul>

        
    </div>

                </div>
                
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</div><div id="s-lg-box-wrapper-31585635" class="s-lg-box-wrapper-31585635">


    <div id="s-lg-box-26876232-container" class="s-lib-box-container">
        <div id="s-lg-box-26876232" class="s-lib-box s-lib-box-std">
                            <h2 class="s-lib-box-title">
                    Digital Collections
                                    </h2>
                        <div id="s-lg-box-collapse-26876232" >
                <div class="s-lib-box-content">
                    <div id="s-lg-content-62720783" class="  clearfix">
    <p>Search for &quot;star spangled banner&quot; in the following Library of Congress digital collections to view both primary sources and related materials about the United States national anthem.</p>

    </div>

    <div class="">
        <ul id="s-lg-link-list-64607557"
            class="s-lg-link-list s-lg-link-list-5">

<li class="">
    
<div id="s-lg-content-62237364" class="s-lg-book clearfix">
    <div class="s-lg-book-props">

                            <a href="https://www.loc.gov/collections/patriotic-melodies/about-this-collection/" target="_blank" onclick="return springSpace.springTrack.trackLink({link: this,_st_type_id: &#039;3&#039;,_st_content_id: &#039;62237364&#039;,_st_inc_return: this});">
        
        <span id="s-lg-book-cover-62237364" class="s-lg-book-cover">
                                        
                
                <img loading="lazy"
                    alt="Patriotic Melodies"
                    src="https://www.loc.gov/static/collections/patriotic-melodies/155_155.jpg"
                    class="pull-left s-lg-book-cover-img-1"
                     />
                    </span>

        <span id="s-lg-book-title-62237364" class="s-lg-book-title"
              >
            Patriotic Melodies
        </span>

                    <span id="s-lg-book-by-62237364" class="s-lg-book-by">
                by
            </span>
        
        <span id="s-lg-book-author-62237364" class="s-lg-book-author">
            Library of Congress
        </span>

                    </a>
        
                
                            
        
        
        
        
        
                
                            <div id="s-lg-book-desc-62237364" class="s-lg-book-desc">
                Patriotic Melodies tells the stories behind many of the songs that have now become part of the American national heritage. A combination of hymns, national songs, music of the theater, radio and television, military themes, and poetry, all of this music demonstrates that while over history many things have changed, this expression of pride and hope remain a constant part of the American experience. This collection includes information about the Star-Spangled Banner.
            </div>
        
    </div>
</div>
</li>




<li class="">
    
<div id="s-lg-content-62237392" class="s-lg-book clearfix">
    <div class="s-lg-book-props">

                            <a href="https://www.loc.gov/collections/songs-of-america/about-this-collection/" target="_blank" onclick="return springSpace.springTrack.trackLink({link: this,_st_type_id: &#039;3&#039;,_st_content_id: &#039;62237392&#039;,_st_inc_return: this});">
        
        <span id="s-lg-book-cover-62237392" class="s-lg-book-cover">
                                        
                
                <img loading="lazy"
                    alt="The Library of Congress Celebrates the Songs of America"
                    src="https://www.loc.gov/static/collections/songs-of-america/155_155.jpg"
                    class="pull-left s-lg-book-cover-img-1"
                     />
                    </span>

        <span id="s-lg-book-title-62237392" class="s-lg-book-title"
              >
            The Library of Congress Celebrates the Songs of America
        </span>

                    <span id="s-lg-book-by-62237392" class="s-lg-book-by">
                by
            </span>
        
        <span id="s-lg-book-author-62237392" class="s-lg-book-author">
            The Library of Congress
        </span>

                    </a>
        
                
                            
        
        
        
        
        
                
                            <div id="s-lg-book-desc-62237392" class="s-lg-book-desc">
                The Songs of America presentation allows you to explore American history as documented in the work of some of our country's greatest composers, poets, scholars, and performers. From popular and traditional songs, to poetic art songs and sacred music, the relationship of song to historical events from the nation's founding to the present is highlighted through more than 80,000 online items. This collection includes information about the Star-Spangled Banner.
            </div>
        
    </div>
</div>
</li>




<li class="">
    
<div id="s-lg-content-62242238" class="s-lg-book clearfix">
    <div class="s-lg-book-props">

                            <a href="https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/" target="_blank" onclick="return springSpace.springTrack.trackLink({link: this,_st_type_id: &#039;3&#039;,_st_content_id: &#039;62242238&#039;,_st_inc_return: this});">
        
        <span id="s-lg-book-cover-62242238" class="s-lg-book-cover">
                                        
                
                <img loading="lazy"
                    alt="Chronicling America: Digital Newspaper Database"
                    src="https://www.loc.gov/static/collections/chronicling-america/155_155.jpg"
                    class="pull-left s-lg-book-cover-img-1"
                     />
                    </span>

        <span id="s-lg-book-title-62242238" class="s-lg-book-title"
              >
            Chronicling America: Digital Newspaper Database
        </span>

                    <span id="s-lg-book-by-62242238" class="s-lg-book-by">
                by
            </span>
        
        <span id="s-lg-book-author-62242238" class="s-lg-book-author">
            National Endowment for the Humanities and the Library of Congress
        </span>

                    </a>
        
                
                            
        
        
        
        
                    <div class="s-lg-book-prop-pubdate">
                Published/Created: 1777-1963
            </div>
        
                
                            <div id="s-lg-book-desc-62242238" class="s-lg-book-desc">
                Search America's historic newspaper pages from 1777-1963 or use the U.S. Newspaper Directory to find information about American newspapers published between 1690-present. Chronicling America is sponsored jointly by the National Endowment for the Humanities and the Library of Congress. This resource includes a wealth of information about the Star-Spangled Banner.
            </div>
        
    </div>
</div>
</li>

        </ul>

        
    </div>

                </div>
                
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</div><div id="s-lg-box-wrapper-30830328" class="s-lg-box-wrapper-30830328">


